<subSubSection id="28956559C848FFEAFCB9F9BBFC405155" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEAFCB9F9BBFC405155" blockId="16.[809,1426,1570,1807]" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9F9BBFB365062" box="[809,1252,1570,1592]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
Diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFC52F9BAFB365062" box="[962,1252,1570,1592]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">Synallaxis amazonica</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCB9F9D9FC48500D" box="[809,922,1601,1623]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9F9D9FC48500D" box="[809,922,1601,1623]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. omissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the forehead, supercilium and face amber (36). However, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFBE1F9F8FAC1502F" box="[1137,1299,1632,1653]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFBE1F9F8FAC1502F" box="[1137,1299,1632,1653]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks any morphological diagnosis compared to 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFA95F9E7FA5B50C9" box="[1285,1417,1662,1684]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFA95F9E7FA5B50C9" box="[1285,1417,1662,1684]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCB9F905FC1750E9" box="[809,965,1693,1715]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caquetensis">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9F905FC1750E9" box="[809,965,1693,1715]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. caquetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFC69F905FBB150E8" box="[1017,1123,1693,1714]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dissors">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFC69F905FBB150E8" box="[1017,1123,1693,1714]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. dissors</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as both the rufous pattern of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCD3F924FC32508B" box="[835,992,1724,1745]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caquetensis">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCD3F924FC32508B" box="[835,992,1724,1745]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. caquetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and olive pattern of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFB58F924FAE0508B" box="[1224,1330,1724,1745]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dissors">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFB58F924FAE0508B" box="[1224,1330,1724,1745]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. dissors</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur in 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C848FFEAFCB9F943FC6C50AA" box="[809,958,1755,1776]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9F943FC6C50AA" box="[809,958,1755,1776]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">S. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including individuals with intermediate plumage.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="28956559C848FFEBFCB9F8A0FD125433" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="16" pageNumber="81" type="description">
<paragraph id="603036D2C848FFEBFCB9F8A0FD125433" blockId="16.[809,1425,1848,1901]" lastBlockId="17.[163,780,197,618]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C848FFEAFCB9F8A0FC655117" box="[809,951,1848,1869]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="81">Description:</emphasis>
Throat sepia (119); breast amber (36), varying individually between robin rufous (340) and chestnut (32); abdomen and flanks olive brown (28), varying individually between clay colour (26) and raw umber (123), with elements of raw umber (123) as a secondary colour; rectrices sepia (119); back and crown olive brown (28), varying individually to Vandyke brown (121), with elements of raw umber (123) and Vandyke brown (121) as the secondary colour; forehead amber (36) varying individually to chestnut (32); supercilium and face amber (36), varying individually to chestnut (32); wing-coverts chestnut (32), varying individually to amber (36); remiges Vandyke brown (121), varying individually to Vandyke brown (221); bill length 
<quantity id="A7779B37C849FFEBFDA9FD8EFD085476" box="[569,730,534,556]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.315" metricValueMax="1.46" metricValueMin="1.17" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" unit="mm" value="13.149999999999999" valueMax="14.6" valueMin="11.7">11.7–14.6 mm</quantity>
; bill depth 3.8–5.0 mm; wing length 
<quantity id="A7779B37C849FFEBFE66FDADFD435411" box="[502,657,565,587]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.85" metricValueMax="6.39" metricValueMin="5.31" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" unit="mm" value="58.5" valueMax="63.9" valueMin="53.1">53.1–63.9 mm</quantity>
; tail length 54.0–72.0 mm, with ten rectrices (see Tables 7, 8).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="28956559C849FFEBFF33FD0AFD2455C4" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="603036D2C849FFEBFF33FD0AFD2455C4" blockId="17.[163,779,658,926]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF33FD0AFE9254FD" box="[163,320,658,679]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Distribution:</emphasis>
Understorey of terra firme forest in 
<collectingCountry id="18987642C849FFEBFF33FD29FF3E549D" box="[163,236,689,711]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFF68FD29FE41549D" box="[248,403,689,711]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF68FD29FE41549D" box="[248,403,689,711]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs from the left bank of the Xingu River, in central Pará, and the right bank of the Amazonas/Solimões River, in Amazonia, southwest to western 
<collectingRegion id="A24BF830C849FFEBFEF4FC96FE285578" box="[356,506,781,803]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="A24BF830C849FFEBFD96FC95FDA55579" box="[518,631,781,803]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="A24BF830C849FFEBFD13FC95FD6A5578" box="[643,696,781,802]" country="Brazil" name="Acre" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Acre</collectingRegion>
and to eastern 
<collectingCountry id="18987642C849FFEBFE90FCB4FEE4551B" box="[256,310,812,833]" name="Peru" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Peru</collectingCountry>
and western 
<collectingCountry id="18987642C849FFEBFE44FCB4FDFA5518" box="[468,552,812,834]" name="Bolivia" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. The distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFF33FCD2FE48553A" box="[163,410,842,864]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF33FCD2FE48553A" box="[163,410,842,864]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Synallaxis amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is represented in 
<figureCitation id="F8B42A57C849FFEBFDCFFCD2FD1B553A" box="[607,713,842,864]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="6.[145,226,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[174,1428,226,1449]" captionTargetId="figure-26@6.[145,1428,195,1478]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing the distribution of sequenced individuals, phylogenetic time tree and plumage analyses for the Synallaxis rutilans group. The areas of endemism recognized by Silva et al. (2005) are highlighted on the map, and distribution points are numbered in accordance with individuals in the tree. The phylogenetic time tree is based on 1539 bp of concatenated ND2 and COI genes. Posterior probability values and the 95% HPD are indicated at each node. Thr, throat; Rec, rectrices; For, forehead; Sup, supercilium; Fac, face; Win, wing-coverts; Rem, remiges; 1st, first colour (main colour); 2nd, second colour (variation ±); 36 (e.g.), colours in Smithe’s catalogue; *, specimen damaged or immature; **, specimen analysed without Smithe’s catalogue; MPEG A, spirit collection specimen; dark grey circles in map and patches in table, specimens with grey plumage pattern; light grey circles and patches, specimens with olive plumage pattern; black circles and patches, specimens with rufous plumage pattern; purple star, type locality of S. r. dissors; red star, type locality of S. r. caquetensis; red star with white spot, type locality of S. r. confinis; blue star, type locality of S. r. amazonica; blue star with a white spot, type locality of S. r. tertia; orange star, type locality of S. r. rutilans; yellow star, type locality of S. r. omissa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530669/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Figures 1</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="F8B42A57C849FFEBFD6DFCD3FCD9553A" box="[765,779,843,864]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="10.[145,224,1191,1213]" captionTargetBox="[145,1401,195,1151]" captionTargetId="figure-187@10.[145,1425,195,1151]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 4. Plumage distribution and geographic variation in the Synallaxis rutilans group. Dark grey circles, specimens with grey-patterned plumage; pale grey circles, specimens with olive-patterned plumage; black circles, specimens with rufous-patterned plumage. Concerning intermediate individuals, any specimen with rufous present on the upperparts was classified in the ‘specimens with rufous-patterned plumage’ group. *Illustrations of birds with the typical plumage of: S. caquetensis (on the left); S. dissors (centre above); S. omissa (right). Area of endemism (AE) and distribution of species of the Synallaxis rutilans group: purple, Guiana EA, S. dissors; red, Napo EA, S. caquetensis; orange, Xingu EA, S. rutilans; yellow, Belém EA, S. omissa; and green, Inambari EA, blue, Rondônia EA and turquoise, Tapajós EA, S. amazonica. *Illustrations from del Hoyo J, Elliott A, Sargatal J, Christie DA, de Juana E, eds. 2017. Handbook of the birds of the world alive. Barcelona: Lynx Edicions (retrieved on 10.11.2017 from http://www.hbw.com)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530681" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530681/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">4</figureCitation>
by the turquoise, blue and green colours of the Tapajós, Rondônia and Inambari endemic areas, respectively.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="28956559C849FFEBFF33FC21FD82506E" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="603036D2C849FFEBFF33FC21FD82506E" blockId="17.[163,781,953,1588]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF33FC21FEC75594" box="[163,277,953,974]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Remarks 7:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFE8DFC21FE005595" author="Vaurie C" box="[285,466,953,975]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 357" refId="ref18086" refString="Vaurie C. 1980. Taxonomy and geographical distribution of the Furnariidae (Aves, Passeriformes). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 166: 1 - 357." type="journal article" year="1980">Vaurie (1980: 117)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that ‘As first reviser, I select 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFF64FC40FD9255B4" authority="(Hellmayr, 1907: 14)" baseAuthorityName="Hellmayr" baseAuthorityPageNumber="14" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[244,576,984,1006]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF64FC40FEB455B7" box="[244,358,984,1005]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">amazonica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFEE3FC40FDEB55B4" author="Hellmayr CE" box="[371,569,984,1006]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 38" refId="ref16256" refString="Hellmayr CE. 1907. Another contribution to the ornithology of the lower Amazonas. Novitates Zoologicae 14: 1 - 38." type="journal article" year="1907">Hellmayr, 1907: 14</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
as the name of the rufous populations, rather than 
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFE63FC6FFDFE5256" box="[499,556,1015,1036]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">tertia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFDA9FC6EFD2D5256" author="Hellmayr CE" box="[569,767,1014,1036]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 38" refId="ref16256" refString="Hellmayr CE. 1907. Another contribution to the ornithology of the lower Amazonas. Novitates Zoologicae 14: 1 - 38." type="journal article" year="1907">Hellmayr, 1907: 15</bibRefCitation>
), which 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFF76FB8DFE0F5271" author="Cory CB &amp; Hellmayr CE" box="[230,477,1045,1067]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 390" refId="ref15366" refString="Cory CB, Hellmayr CE. 1925. Catalogue of birds of the Americas. Furnariidae - Dendrocolaptidae. Publications of the Field Museum of Natural History, Zoological Series 13: 1 - 390." type="book chapter" year="1925">Cory &amp; Hellmayr (1925)</bibRefCitation>
noted subsequently is ‘closely similar’ to 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFE86FBACFE585213" baseAuthorityName="Hellmayr" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[278,394,1076,1097]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFE86FBACFE585213" box="[278,394,1076,1097]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’. 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFE0BFBACFF07523D" authority="Hellmayr, 1907" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFE0BFBACFD485213" box="[411,666,1076,1097]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Synallaxis r. amazonica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFD31FBACFF07523D" author="Hellmayr CE" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 38" refId="ref16256" refString="Hellmayr CE. 1907. Another contribution to the ornithology of the lower Amazonas. Novitates Zoologicae 14: 1 - 38." type="journal article" year="1907">Hellmayr, 1907</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, was described simultaneously with 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFDDFFBCAFE9452DC" authority="Hellmayr, 1907" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="tertia">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFDDFFBCAFCD95232" box="[591,779,1106,1128]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Synallaxis r. tertia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFF33FBE9FE9452DC" author="Hellmayr CE" box="[163,326,1137,1159]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 38" refId="ref16256" refString="Hellmayr CE. 1907. Another contribution to the ornithology of the lower Amazonas. Novitates Zoologicae 14: 1 - 38." type="journal article" year="1907">Hellmayr, 1907</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and from the moment that 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFDE9FBE9FCD852DD" author="Vaurie C" box="[633,778,1137,1159]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 357" refId="ref18086" refString="Vaurie C. 1980. Taxonomy and geographical distribution of the Furnariidae (Aves, Passeriformes). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 166: 1 - 357." type="journal article" year="1980">Vaurie (1980)</bibRefCitation>
considered these two names to be subjective synonyms he acted in accordance with Article 24.2.2 of the Code, wherein it is stated that determining the precedence of names is the role of the first reviser. We maintain the understanding of 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFF33FA92FEF9537A" author="Vaurie C" box="[163,299,1290,1312]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 357" refId="ref18086" refString="Vaurie C. 1980. Taxonomy and geographical distribution of the Furnariidae (Aves, Passeriformes). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 166: 1 - 357." type="journal article" year="1980">Vaurie (1980)</bibRefCitation>
that 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFECFFA93FE6C537A" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" box="[351,446,1291,1312]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="tertia">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFECFFA93FE6C537A" box="[351,446,1291,1312]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S. r.tertia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior subjective synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFF33FAB1FEE75365" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" box="[163,309,1321,1343]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF33FAB1FEE75365" box="[163,309,1321,1343]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S.r.amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but we think that 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFE7FFAB1FD515365" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" box="[495,643,1321,1343]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFE7FFAB1FD515365" box="[495,643,1321,1343]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S.r.amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should not be the name applied to‘rufous’ populations of the 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFDF3FAD0FD1B5307" box="[611,713,1352,1373]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilans">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFDF3FAD0FD1B5307" box="[611,713,1352,1373]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S.rutilans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Populations with diagnostically rufous plumage are named 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFF33FA1DFDE353C0" authority="Chapman, 1914" authorityName="Chapman" authorityYear="1914" box="[163,561,1413,1435]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caquetensis">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF33FA1DFE5B53C1" box="[163,393,1413,1435]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">Synallaxis caquetensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFE1DFA1DFDE353C0" author="Chapman FM" box="[397,561,1413,1435]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="603 - 637" refId="ref15272" refString="Chapman FM. 1914. Diagnoses of apparently new Colombian birds III. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 33: 603 - 637." type="journal article" year="1914">Chapman, 1914</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, considering the 
<typeStatus id="BF348870C849FFEBFD4DFA1DFCDE53C0" box="[733,780,1413,1434]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">type</typeStatus>
locality and the results of our analysis.Thus, in fact, the act of 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFF33FA5AFEFA5382" author="Vaurie C" box="[163,296,1474,1496]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 357" refId="ref18086" refString="Vaurie C. 1980. Taxonomy and geographical distribution of the Furnariidae (Aves, Passeriformes). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 166: 1 - 357." type="journal article" year="1980">Vaurie(1980)</bibRefCitation>
as first reviser fixed the priority of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFDE7FA5BFCD95382" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" box="[631,779,1475,1496]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFDE7FA5BFCD95382" box="[631,779,1475,1496]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S.r.amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ahead of 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFF6CFA79FE8553AD" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" box="[252,343,1505,1527]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="tertia">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFF6CFA79FE8553AD" box="[252,343,1505,1527]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S.r.tertia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but application of the name 
<taxonomicName id="A78F4D51C849FFEBFDE5FA79FCD953AD" authorityName="Hellmayr" authorityYear="1907" box="[629,779,1505,1527]" class="Aves" family="Furnariidae" genus="Synallaxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rutilans" subSpecies="amazonica">
<emphasis id="52FBEAC0C849FFEBFDE5FA79FCD953AD" box="[629,779,1505,1527]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="82">S. r.amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
proposed here is distinct from that used by 
<bibRefCitation id="041E4B23C849FFEBFDD5F998FD19504C" author="Vaurie C" box="[581,715,1536,1558]" pageId="17" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 357" refId="ref18086" refString="Vaurie C. 1980. Taxonomy and geographical distribution of the Furnariidae (Aves, Passeriformes). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 166: 1 - 357." type="journal article" year="1980">Vaurie (1980)</bibRefCitation>
and is not affected by his judgment as first reviser.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
